SIMPLE: skelp
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Skelp
<hw>Skelp</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Prov. E.
<ets>skelp</ets> to kick severely, to move rapidly; Gael.
<ets>sgealp</ets>, n., a slap with the palm of the hand, v., to strike
with the palm of the hand.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A blow; a smart
stroke.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Brockett.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A squall; also, a heavy fall of rain.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skelp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Skelp
<hw>Skelp</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike; to
slap.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark> <rj><au>C. Reade.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form into skelp, as a plate or bar of iron by
rolling; also, to bend round (a skelp) in tube making.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skelp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Skelp
<hw>Skelp</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wrought-iron plate from which a gun
barrel or pipe is made by bending and welding the edges together, and
drawing the thick tube thus formed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skelter</ent>⟦br⟧
